             and H. Williams - I do not know those persons - (read).</p>
               <p>To Mr. Frost, Perry-street, Somer's-town. October 4, 1828.</p>
               <p>SIR, - Doubtless ere this you are aware of your loss; it is useless our denying it, therefore we shall make a full confission, and trust to your clemency and kindness. Driven by distress, starvation, and without a place to shelter our heads, when we left Perry-street, we entered your apartment, and took the articles, of which we now return the duplicats, being well aware that they are of greater value than what they are pledged for, and with the intention of making our crime as light a possable; do not emmagin for a moment that we returne them out of bravado - no, rest assured such is not our intentin, but to attone in part for our crimes, and make your loss as little as possable. Sir, I implore, that after this confession you will deal as leniant with us as possable, and not let the law take its course; that we are deserving of yours and the laws correction we well know, but we allso know that you cannot be so unfeeling has to deprive a fellow creature of liberty and reputation, for commiting a crime when urged to it by hungar and distress; under all curcumstances, we we will rely upon your humanity, and throw ourselves entirely upon your mercy -We remain, your verry humble servants, &amp;c, G. JONES and H. WILLIAMS.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-240-person2100">
                  RICHARD 
                  HARTLEY WALL
               <interp inst="t18281204-240-person2100" type="surname" value="HARTLEY WALL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-240-person2100" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-240-person2100" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . The prisoner was brought to the office on the 29th; I searched him - Frost produced this letter containing six duplicates.</p>
               <p>MRS. FROST. I received this letter by the post; it contained six duplicates of the articles produced; the prisoner left the premises on the night of the robbery - I had not heard that he inteuded to go before.</p>
               <p>The several pawnbrokers here identified the different duplicates produced.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18281204-240-person2101">
                  MARY 
                  HEWITT
               <interp inst="t18281204-240-person2101" type="surname" value="HEWITT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-240-person2101" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18281204-240-person2101" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. My husband rents the house; the prisoner had lived there a fortnight and a few<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182812040123"></xptr>days, and left on the night of the robbery - he paid 4s. 6d. a week; he had given no notice at all, nor did he tell us where he was going to - a person named Murray lived in the room with the prisoner, but they came by the name of Jones and Williams, but I did not know which was which; my husband told them if they could not pay they had better leave - I believe that was on the Tuesday, and the robbery was on Thursday; they promised to pay on the Wednesday, but did not.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The landlord of the house gave us notice to quit if we did not pay our rent the night following; the letters are not my hand-writing.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 22.</p>
